SYMBOLIC POLITICS: THE LITERATURE
Although studies of the behavior of elected officials have focused primarily on the relationship between officials’ actions and the distribution of tangible rewards to constituents or interest groups, social scientists have recognized that such actions may also be examined in terms of symbolic rewards- what they mean to the public (e.g., Edelman, 1964, 1971; Gusfield, 1963; Cobb s( Elder, 1976; Andenaes, 1974; Stolz, 1983, 1985). Symbolic rewards derive their meaning from an audience’s response rather than the act itself. Criminal law may perform three symbolic functions- reassurance, moral educative, and providing a model for the states (Stolz, 1983, 1985).
In examining the influence of symbolism on regulatory policy, Murray Edelman (1964, 1971) focused on the reassurance/threat function. He asserts that any controversial or important political act serves in part as a condensation symbol.’ The act evokes a mass response, because it symbolizes a threat or a reassurance to the onlooker (Edelrnan, 1964, p. 7). According to Edelman (1964, p. 31), the onlooker to whom the symbol is directed is that segment of the public that is responsive to symbols that oversimplify and distort; sees

