and thinks in terms of stereotypes, personalization, and oversimplification; and cannot tolerate ambiguous and complex situations. Symbolization induces a feeling of well-being (1964, p. 38).
According to Edelman (1964, p. 15), our permanent legal and political institutions reassure people. These institutions are permeated by rituals, which promote conformity and evoke joy in that conformity (1964, p. 16). A key function of our persisting political institutionselections, political discussions, legislatures, courts, and administrationis to quiet resentments and doubts about particular political acts, reaffirm belief in the fundamental rationality and democratic character of the system, and thus fix conforming habits of future behavior (Eldelman, 1964, p. 17). Each involves activity that reinforces the impression of a political system designed to translate individual wants into public policy (1964, p. 17).
Anthropologist Weatherford (1985) examines the rituals and ritualization of Congress and the congressional legislative process. He suggests that the creeping ritualization of Congress portrays much of the same process as that of the escalating sacrifices of the Aztecs, a process which contained the seeds of destruction and eventually brought down that society. While not predicting the collapse of American society, Weatherford does suggest that the results of the ritualization of the legislative process are profound and far-reaching (1985, pp. 185-186). He further asserts that Congress has rivals for power, with the greatest potential threat coming from the voters. Yet, while concluding that Congress has to worry about what its constituency thinks of it and that that opinion has steadily declined throughout this century, he also suggests that Congress still has little to fear from the voters (1985, pp. 258-260).
Social scientists have differed in their interpretation of the significance of symbolic reassurance to the public. For example, Edelman depicts it as irrational, while Joseph Gusfield (1963, p. 182183) asserts that symbolic reassurance fulfills real, but intangible needs. Examining federal capital punishment legislation (1983) and the 1984 omnibus crime legislation (1985), Stolz found both types of symbolic reassurance.
Stolz (1983, p. 161) further argues that while the symbolic reassurance generated by the passage of criminal laws suggests activity on the part of the lawmakers, it often signifies an ineffective but popularly acceptable response. In addition, she found that Members of Congress perceive federal criminaljustice legislation as communicating a substantive message to the public and as providing policy direction to the states (Stolz, 1983, pp. 163-171 and 1985, pp. 312-315). She concludes that in addition to the reassurance function, the symbolic

