Scholars have debated (for example, Andenaes, 1974; Zimring Sr
Hawkins, 1973; Hawkins, 1969; Arnold, 1935; Berns, 1979) how criminal laws and sanction perform a moral educative function. It appears, however, that there are two audiences to whom the message is sent -the lawbreaker and the law-abiding. Moreover, the moral educative process is complex.
Berns (1979, pp. 507-508), for example, has argued that law not only blames but rewards. By rewarding praises to the law-abiding, it teaches law-abidingness and educates the law-abiding as well as the lawbreaker. In effect, criminal law confers prestige on the law-abiding and withdraws support from those defined as the criminal element. Passage of criminal justice legislation can therefore be interpreted as a “gesture of deference” or an act of “degradation“(Gusfield, 1963, p. 15; Stolz, 1983, p. 167).
Andenaes’ study of criminal law (1974, pp. 116-125) underscores the complexity of the moral educative function. He asserts that the moral educative effect of criminal law can be direct or indirect. The direct effects include generating feelings of obligation to obey and respect the law, making citizens aware of the morally harmful character of certain behavior thereby functioning as a moral eye-opener, and upholding moral inhibitions by making an authoritative statement about wrongdoing. Indirectly punishment reduces and neutralizes bad example, acting as a vaccination against the temptation to follow the example. It also helps to shape the moral education of the young.
That federal laws and programs provide models to the states has been recognized by Presidents, Members of Congress and national commissions. The audience toward which the federal government’s symbolic actions are directed is state officials, as well as the public and interest groups (Stolz, 1983, pp. 170-171). Federal laws and programs can serve as models by example, by funding programs that promote a particular policy, or by making receipt of federal funds contingent on states implementing a particular policy or program.
Numerous examples of each of these approaches - example, carrot, and stick- exist in criminal justice and other policy areas. President Nixon sought to develop the Federal Bureau of Prisons into a model for the states, a concept that was supported by the National Advisory Commission on Criminal Justice Standards and Goals. The Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention and the Law Enforcement Assistance Administration provided funds to the states in support of programs that reflected the federal government’s perspective on good juvenile justice or good criminal justice policy. Threatened loss of

