METHODS
To examine congressional anti-drug efforts, the case method was employed. Congressional Record reports of House and Senate floor action, committee reports, newspaper and journal accounts, discussions with congressional staff, and participant observation were used to develop the case studies of the legislative process ;hat led to the enactment of the Anti-Drug Abuse Acts of 1986 and 1988. Between September 1985 and September 1989, the author served on the staff of the House of Representatives Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control (hereafter denoted as SCNAC). This position permitted firsthand observation of the evolution of the anti-drug abuse legislation.
CONGRESS’ WAR ON DRUGS
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986
On June 19, 1986, Len Bias, a young and talented University of Maryland basketball player, who had just been drafted by the Boston Celtics, died of an overdose of cocaine. Although public and media attention to the drug issue had been growing, Bias’ death seems to have been the event that focused that concern and galvanized congressional anti-drug efforts in the 99th Congress. When Members of Congress returned to their districts during the 4th of July recess, they found that drug abuse had emerged as a major constituent concern (SCNAC, 1986, p. 28).
Responding to this concern, on July 23, 1986, House Speaker Thomas P. O’Neill convened a meeting of House committee chairmen with jurisdiction over the issues of drug trafficking and abuse. The purpose of the meeting was to develop a comprehensive drug initiative before the 99th Congress adjourned. The Speaker designated Majority Leader Jim Wright as the coordinator of committee efforts to bring a comprehensive drug bill to the House for a vote by September 10, 1986 (SCNAC, 1986, p. 28).

