The House began consideration of H.R. 5484 on September 10, 1986. Final passage, with amendments, occurred on September 11. The bill was sent to the Senate, which passed the bill with amendments. Instead of a formal conference, differences between the House and Senate versions were resolved through a series of amendments passed by the House and Senate.
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was enacted by the House and Senate on October 17, 1986. Congress achieved this feat between July and October - without hearings, without a formal conference - by taking short-cuts through the legislative process. During the House floor debate, one Congressman, although supporting the legislation, even went so far as to chastise his colleagues for responding to three weeks of media and newspaper coverage and attempting a quick-fur approach to a problem that would take years not weeks to fur (Congressional Record, September 10, 1986: H6598). The President signed the AntiDrug Abuse Act into law on October 27, 1986, culminating the first effort by Congress in fifteen years to enact major anti-drug legislation.
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988
On the eve of adjournment in 1988, the 100th Congress enacted anti-drug legislation. Unlike 1986, congressional action was not galvanized by a single event, but by a number of factors. The drug problem remained a major public concern, even after enactment of the 1986 legislation, as evidenced by public opinion polls (for example CBS/New York Times Poll, October 28, 1986, and May 9, 1988; Los Angeles Times Poll, October 13, 1988; NBC News/Wall Street Journal Poll, September 22, 1986, and September 30, 1988). New dimensions of the problem continued to emerge.

