In the waning hours of the 100th Congress on October 22, 1988, the House and Senate enacted the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988. The legislation included the new user accountability proposals, a death penalty for drug kingpins, and a “drug czar,” as well as additional funding for programs created under the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. As in 1986, the feat was accomplished by taking short-cuts through the legislative process. The President signed the bill into law on November 18.
Anti-Drug/Anti-Crime Legislation: 1990
While the drug issue remained a concern to the public during the lOlst Congress, it was subsumed under the crime issue. Both the Senate (on July 11, 1990) and House (on October 5, 1990) passed anticrime legislation, which included anti-drug provisions. By October, however, other concerns dominated congressional and public attention, decreasing the likelihood that Congress would enact anti-drug/anti-crime legislation before adjournment. Congress became locked in conflict with the President over the federal budget. The public was focused on the state of the nation’s savings and loan institutions. American troops were being sent to Iraq. Congress was expected to adjourn by October 13th, but the session continued.
On October 23, the Senate received the House crime bill, H.R. 5269, and struck all provisions after the enacting clause, substituting the language of S. 1970, as amended. Conferees on the crime bill were appointed for the Senate and House on October 23 and 25, respectively. While no formal conference was held, a final package was agreed to, passed by both houses, and signed into law by the President in November 1990. Congress had again enacted anti-drug/anti-crime legislation on the eve of elections.
