The outflow of public and media attention following the cocainerelated death of basketball star Len Bias communicated to the Congress that the American public believed that there was a drug problem. The efforts of the 99th Congress to enact anti-drug legislation prior to the 1986 elections were clearly directed toward reassuring the public that Congress was "doing something" about the nation's drug problem. The debate, reported in the Congressional Record (September 10,11,26-30, October 8, 10-15, 1986), includes statements by member after member that the Congress must act to respond to public concerns about the nation's drug problem. Congressman Charles Range1 went so far as to say:
I know that this being an election year, there are those who would challenge the integrity of the House, or indeed the Congress, as to why we are doing it (passing the drug bill) at this time, as though responding to the demand of the American people that we do something would not be sufficient (Congressional Record, September 10, 1986, p. H6521).
Congress' desire to reassure the public was also reflected in the way that they described the legislation. House members characterized the legislation as bipartisan, a total mobilization against the most serious problem, a comprehensive response, a battle plan, a real war on drugs, and a signal to the American people that we (the Congress) are ready to get on with it, to begin waging the war on drugs. Senators underscored the need for the Congress to respond to the drug problem and not to shirk its responsibility to the American people to swiftly and surely address the drug abuse epidemic. Consensus that something needed to be done was the overriding theme.
The substantive message, which the 1986 congressional debate on the omnibus anti-drug legislation sent to the American public, was clear. The United States had a serious drug problem and that problem threatened the nation. The American people were victims of that threat. A war must be waged against the drug epidemic. Through the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, Congress was providing the tools to fight that war. The public could be reassured.
