Congressional efforts to enact anti-drug legislation reflect Congress' need to reassure the public that something was being done about a problem that had raised national concern. Actions and rhetoric of both Democratic and Republican Members of Congress indicated recognition of this need. At the same time, there was no evidence that individual members felt that they would not be reelected because of Congress' failure to address the problem. Rather, the need to reassure the public seemed to reflect a need felt by incumbents of both political parties to show that the Congress, as an institution, can respond to public concerns and thereby raise the public's opinion of Congress.
