Model for the States
The 1986 and 1988 anti-drug legislation reflected Congress's desire to provide a model for the states. Included in the laws were provisions indicative of three ways federal laws could serve as a model- example, carrot, and stick. Providing sources of funding to the states to support certain programs was a key component of 1986 legislation. The 1988 legislation expanded these programs. Promotion of federal policy by example and, particularly by stick, was more evident in 1988, although not all were included in the final legislation.
The Anti-Drug Abuse Acts of 1986 and 1988 provided funds to states and localities for anti-drug programs. The 1986 anti-drug legislation established block grant programs to provide funds to states and localities for drug abuse education and drug law enforcement programs. Federal funds for drug abuse treatment were already provided through the Alcohol, Drug Abuse, and Mental Health Block grant, but additional funds were provided through a new substance abuse block grant. As is generally true of block grant legislation, the anti-drug abuse programs provided a wide degree of latitude.
The 1988 omnibus drug legislation provided additional funds for the block grant programs. Additional discretionary grants programs for drug abuse prevention were also created. Further, the drug law enforcement program was expanded in scope and renamed the Edward Byrne Program in honor of a slain New York police officer.
The 1988 legislation also included a very distinct case of the federal government attempting to provide states with an example of what state
drug laws should be. Title VII, Subtitle 0- Miscellaneous established
a "National Commission on Measured Responses to Achieve a DrugFree America by 1995" to develop a proposed uniform code of state laws that represent measured responses to achieve a Drug Free America by 1995. The law specifically directed the Commission to consider such measures as appropriate penalties for drug offenses, participation in rehabilitation and treatment programs, appropriate use of drug testing, efforts to educate the public about the dangers of drugs, forfeiture of assets of violators of state drug laws, and cooperative ventures among federal, state and local levels.

