Among the proposals and amendments considered during congressional deliberations on the 1988 anti-drug legislation were numerous examples of the "stick approach." For example, Representative McCollum (Republican) offered an amendment to the 1988 drug bill which would have withheld a portion of federal highway funds from states that did not pass laws requiring suspension of the driver's license of persons convicted of drug-related offenses. Representative Anderson (Democrat) offered a substitute amendment to provide up to $125 million in grants, over three years, to states that implemented drug enforcement programs with similar license provisions. The final legislation established a pilot grant program- to be carried out in not more than four states-for random drug testing of applicants for a driver's license. Participating states were to deny a license for at least a year, if an individual was found to have used an illicit drug.
The provisions of the 1986 and 1988 legislation sent a complex message to the states. The programs providing funds for drug education, prevention, and treatment sent a message that the Congress expected states to implement drug education programs in the schools, inform citizens about drug abuse, and provide assistance to those who had become addicted to drugs. At the same time, provisions such as the driver's license pilot program, the proposed model state legislation, and some of the program areas to be funded through the drug law enforcement grants sent the message to state officials that Congress expected the states to implement "tougher drug laws." During the congressional debates on the anti-drug legislation, members spoke of creating a comprehensive approach to the nation's drug problem. Whether the actual outcome can be said to be a comprehensive, or just a complex, approach, the message sent to the states reflected a similar approach.
Federal anti-drug legislation enacted in 1986 and 1988 reflected congressional concern with the symbolic aspects of such laws. Both the 1986 and the 1988 laws were very clearly enacted in response to public concern about the drug problem. Moreover, both laws were to send a moral message to the American public, but the nature of the message changed. The 1986 legislation indicated that information disseminated through programs funded by Congress would prevent drug use. The 1988 legislation, while continuing and increasing the funding for these programs, also sent a punitive message and reflected the assumption that the threat of punishment through law deters behavior. Finally, the

