IMPLICATIONS AND CONCLUSIONS
The case studies, findings, and analyses presented above describe the influence of symbolic politics on the development of federal antidrug/anti-crime legislation. Although the findings may not portend consequences as dire as those experienced by the Aztecs, they do raise a number of issues and questions regarding the content and formulation of drug and criminal justice policy; the congressional policy-making process, in general; and Congress’ ability to respond effectively to national problems. Responding swiftly to public concerns prior to an election may keep incumbents in office, but at what cost to the nation, if the solutions offered do not effectively address the problem?
While enactment of the 1986 and 1988 anti-drug legislation, as well as the 1984 and 1990 anti-crime bills, suggests activity on the part of the Congress, there appears to have been little time or opportunity to evaluate and assess the substantive merits of the provisions of the legislation. With respect to specific policies, available congressional documents tell us little about the impact of alternative policies included as opposed to those rejected, research findings regarding the merits of one approach versus another, the real versus politically acceptable cost of the policies considered and ultimately enacted, the impact of the cost of the new legislation on those responsible for implementing it, the cost effectiveness of proposals, or the workability versus the political feasibility of a provision. Some proposals were scrutinized by the responsible congressional committees. Many others were not, particularly those that were the result of last minute compromises. Were the former proposals better than the latter? Time may tell, but Congress’ documentation on this legislation provides us with little information on which to make that assessment.
Congress’ approach to the problems of drugs and crime has been to enact omnibus or comprehensive legislation. The approach allows Congress to reassure the public that they are responding to a complex problem with a complex approach and to respond to concerns of different segments of the public (e.g., provide drug treatment to assuage the liberal elements and additional sanctions for those who believe punishment is the answer). The omnibus approach permits a complex, but not necessarily an integrated response. In fact, the diverse policies enacted could conflict and ultimately prove counterproductive. While the omnibus legislation is considered by the full House and Senate, the debate focuses primarily on certain pre-approved amendments. There

