This study also raises some interesting questions regarding the behavior of Congress as an institution. As noted above, there was no evidence found of individual members fearing they would not be reelected because of public concern about drugs and crime. Rather, as was the case with the anti-crime legislation in 1984 (Stolz, 1985), the need to address the drug problem and to reassure the public was an
institutional need to show the public that Congress - the incumbents -
could handle the problem. This suggests a link between the behavior and fate of incumbents and the function of political institutions to reassure the public. If Congress can pass laws that reassure the public that its concerns are being addressed, then the impression that the political system is translating individual wants into public policy is reinforced.
If by so doing Congress reinforces the public’s sense of well-being, then perhaps there is no threat to the republic. Yet, drugs and crime remain major public concerns. The costs of the systems created to address drugs and crime in America continue to escalate. Congress may continue to enact anti-drug/anti-crime legislation on the eve of elections, but will the public ultimately see the discrepancy between Congress’ actions and solutions? Will Congress’ attention to symbols undermine it as an institution? Will the public challenge Congress, and throw the rascals out?
In conclusion, this article began with the thesis that congressional efforts to enact anti-drug legislation in 1986 and 1988 and specific provisions within that legislation could be explained in terms of symbolic politics, acts directed toward the general public. Analyzing congressional anti-drug and anti-crime efforts in this context, however, raises issues, but leaves unanswered very serious questions about congressional policy-making and the future of Congress as an institution.
